  "docs": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "kind": "summary",
        "title": "Summary",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Return the normalized sinc function."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "The sinc function is equal to :math:`\\sin(\\pi x)/(\\pi x)` for any argument\n:math:`x\\ne 0`. ``sinc(0)`` takes the limit value 1, making ``sinc`` not\nonly everywhere continuous but also infinitely differentiable."
          },
          {
            "type": "directive",
            "name": "note",
            "body": "",
            "raw": ".. note::"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "    Note the normalization factor of ``pi`` used in the definition.\n    This is the most commonly used definition in signal processing.\n    Use ``sinc(x / np.pi)`` to obtain the unnormalized sinc function\n    :math:`\\sin(x)/x` that is more common in mathematics."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "parameters",
        "title": "Parameters",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "x",
            "type": "ndarray",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "Array (possibly multi-dimensional) of values for which to calculate\n``sinc(x)``."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "returns",
        "title": "Returns",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "out",
            "type": "ndarray",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "``sinc(x)``, which has the same shape as the input."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "notes",
        "title": "Notes",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "The name sinc is short for \"sine cardinal\" or \"sinus cardinalis\"."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "The sinc function is used in various signal processing applications,\nincluding in anti-aliasing, in the construction of a Lanczos resampling\nfilter, and in interpolation."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "For bandlimited interpolation of discrete-time signals, the ideal\ninterpolation kernel is proportional to the sinc function."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "examples",
        "title": "Examples",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> import numpy as np\n>>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n>>> x = np.linspace(-4, 4, 41)\n>>> np.sinc(x)\n array([-3.89804309e-17,  -4.92362781e-02,  -8.40918587e-02, # may vary\n        -8.90384387e-02,  -5.84680802e-02,   3.89804309e-17,\n        6.68206631e-02,   1.16434881e-01,   1.26137788e-01,\n        8.50444803e-02,  -3.89804309e-17,  -1.03943254e-01,\n        -1.89206682e-01,  -2.16236208e-01,  -1.55914881e-01,\n        3.89804309e-17,   2.33872321e-01,   5.04551152e-01,\n        7.56826729e-01,   9.35489284e-01,   1.00000000e+00,\n        9.35489284e-01,   7.56826729e-01,   5.04551152e-01,\n        2.33872321e-01,   3.89804309e-17,  -1.55914881e-01,\n       -2.16236208e-01,  -1.89206682e-01,  -1.03943254e-01,\n       -3.89804309e-17,   8.50444803e-02,   1.26137788e-01,\n        1.16434881e-01,   6.68206631e-02,   3.89804309e-17,\n        -5.84680802e-02,  -8.90384387e-02,  -8.40918587e-02,\n        -4.92362781e-02,  -3.89804309e-17])"
          },
          {
